 Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Walton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Walton, which are named with Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Briton, serf’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>), <i>wald</i> ‘woodland’, <i>wall</i> ‘wall’, or <i>wælla</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","History: George Walton (1741–1804) signed the Declaration of Independence. He was born in Prince Edward County, VA, whither his grandfather had emigrated from England in 1682. He moved to Savannah, GA, and became governor of GA and a prominent jurist."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":40,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":53,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":62,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John de Walton was born in 1275, in Wivenhoe, Essex, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Walton. In 1330, his occupation is listed as sheriff of essex and hertfordshire . He died about 1341, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1275–about 1341":"1275–umbes 1341","1272–1332":"1272–1332","1293–1358":"1293–1358","1275–1341":"1275–1341","about 1293":"umbes 1293","from 1330 to 1332":"1330 kuni 1332","1275":"1275","1341":"1341","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","about 1332":"umbes 1332","about 1341":"umbes 1341","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wivenhoe, Essex, England":"Wivenhoe, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1275–about 1341":"1275–noin 1341","1272–1332":"1272–1332","1293–1358":"1293–1358","1275–1341":"1275–1341","about 1293":"noin 1293","from 1330 to 1332":"vuodesta 1330 vuoteen 1332","1275":"1275","1341":"1341","1272":"1272","1293":"1293","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1358":"1358","1453":"1453","1332":"1332","about 1332":"noin 1332","about 1341":"noin 1341","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wivenhoe, Essex, England":"Wivenhoe, Essex, England"},"fr":